The Publisher has sent me the Book of “Selections,”John Ruskin, Selections from the Writings of John Ruskin (1861), pbd. by Smith, Elder & Co. as promised; and it is my constant companion, these evenings, in the few leisure hours I have;—awakening in me, seriously, the wish that every drawing-room in her Majesty’s dominions were provided with a Copy, and able to read it with feelings similar to mine! It is many a day and year since I met with any Book the spirit of whh (to say nothing of its lively felicitous expression) is so accordant with what I reckon best & truest.— The idea of the PublisherSmith, Elder & Co. prefaced the volume with an “Advertisement”: “[T]his volume has originated in suggestions, from numerous quarters, that a book of the kind would be acceptable to a large circle of readers. … The publishers think it right to add that Mr. Ruskin, though tacitly consenting to this publication, has taken no part in making the selections, and is in no way responsible for the appearance of the volume” (Ruskin, Selections [iii]). Selections was compiled by William Smith Williams (1800–1875), the publisher’s reader, and William Henry Harrison (1795–1878), Ruskin’s editor and family friend. John James Ruskin sent TC’s letter to his son, who replied, 5 Dec.: “I have your nice and kind letter … enclosing Carlyle’s, most interesting and kind also. … As he says the extracts are right, I have not a word more to say against them. It is the books which must be wrong” (E. T. Cook, The Life of Ruskin [1911] 2:42). Ruskin then wrote to his father, 9 Dec.: “Don’t send the book of extracts to anybody, that you can help. … It is a form of mince-pie which I have no fancy for. My crest is all very well as long as it means Pork, but I don’t love being made into sausages” (Life 2:42). Ruskin’s crest was a boar’s head. was surely altogether good; multitudes of people, who could not get access to the big expensive works, will be furnished with this as a kind of manual; and no ingenuous soul will read any bit of it (at least any bit I have yet fallen in with) whh will not have a tendency to do him good, as well as give him pleasure. The Book is well printed, unusually correct for most part; the Portrait has a good resemblance à la Richmond:
