       it is altogether a pleasant little companion, and a profitable in these bad times;—and I am much obliged to you for my individual share in the adventure.

If you are still to have some time, you must try Chelsea again. This week I am on a kind of holiday: the last I shall have for a very long while. Tomorrow Evg (Tuesday 7½ p.m.); my Wife is returned, and we shd have an hour free for you.Parkes noted that “throughout the first nine months of 1862” he “often spent part of an evening with Mr. and Mrs. Carlyle” (Parkes 1:164). On one of these visits he suggested: “I have sometimes thought that it would be a good thing for a man like me—imperfectly educated and with many things always pressing upon his time, to put aside all books, save ten or twelve authors, and thoroughly master them. … He made some curt observation which I interpreted as unfavourable. … When I called again he said, ‘I have jotted down some books for you, if you carry out your plan of studying a few authors,’ and he fetched me the list written in pencil” (Parkes 1:165). For the list, see 210 above ; The authors and works (in the order TC cites them) are: Alexander Pope, 18th-cent. English poet; Jonathan Swift, Gulliver’s Travels (1726) and The Battle of the Books (1704); David Dalrymple, Lord Hailes, Annals of Scotland (1776); William Camden, Britain; or, a Choro-graphicall Description of the most flourishing Kingdomes, England, Scotland, and Ireland. … Written first in Latin … translated newly into English by Philemon Holland, 2 pts. (1610); Snorro Sturleson, The Heimskringla; or, Chronicle of the Kings of Norway, trans. Samuel Laing, 3 vols. (1844); George Anson, A Voyage to the South Seas (1745); John Byron, Byron’s Narrative of the Loss of the Wager … on the Coast of Patagonia, from the Year 1740, till their Arrival in England, 1746 (1768) (see 30:106 TC to JN, 5 Nov. 1855
); Oliver Goldsmith, Vicar of Wakefield (1766); Tobias Smollett, Humphry Clinker (1771); Samuel Richardson and Henry Fielding, 18th-cent. English novelists; Arabian Nights’ Entertainment; Miguel Cervantes, Don Quixote; Works of the Late Doctor Benjamin Franklin, Consisting of His Life Written by Himself, Together with Essays, 2 vols. (1793); William Shenstone, 18th-cent. English poet; James Boswell, Life of Samuel Johnson, LL.D. (1791) and A Journal of a Tour to the Hebrides with Samuel Johnson, LL.D (1785) (for TC’s comment on Boswell’s Journal, see TC to Lord A and Lady A LALA , 5 Nov. ); Plutarch’s Lives, trans. John Dryden, rev. A. H. Clough, 5 vols. (Boston, 1859). TC’s list for Parkes concluded on a second page (see inset, 210 TC to HP, 15 Sept. 1862
): Thomas Fuller, The History of the Worthies of England (1662); Geoffrey Chaucer, 14th-cent. English poet. (Parkes 1:164–165; Wilson 5:445–46). TC wrote a similar list (including some of the same authors) for the Ashburtons; see TC to Lord A and Lady A LALA , 5 Nov. Parkes also commented: “Another book which Mr. Carlyle frequently urged upon my notice was Collins’s Peerage … from which, he said, he had learned more of English history than from all other books put together” (Parkes 1:165); Arthur Collins, Peerage of England (first pbd. 1709; definitive edn., 9 vols., 1812).
